WEBVTT

00:02.168 --> 00:02.936
(male narrator)
Last on
"Perfect Strangers..."

00:02.969 --> 00:04.771
<i>♪ ...yankee Dood‐lee dandy ♪</i>

00:04.805 --> 00:07.173
♪ Yankee Dood‐lee do or die ♪

00:07.207 --> 00:09.209
I passed
my citizenship test.

00:09.242 --> 00:10.577
[cheering]

00:12.245 --> 00:13.714
See, I arranged
to have Balki’s mother

00:13.747 --> 00:15.582
flown over from Mypos
so she could witness

00:15.616 --> 00:17.518
Balki being sworn in
as a US citizen.

00:18.151 --> 00:19.686
Balki, Balki.

00:19.720 --> 00:21.588
‐My Balki! Balki...
‐Mama!

00:21.622 --> 00:23.524
Oh, my mama, mama!

00:23.557 --> 00:26.026
[speaking in Myposian]

00:27.427 --> 00:28.729
She thought she was
coming over here

00:28.762 --> 00:31.765
to see me get
my driver’s license?

00:31.798 --> 00:33.734
Either I go back
to Mypos with her or...

00:34.801 --> 00:36.537
...I am no longer her son.

00:38.404 --> 00:40.774
Well, I guess this is...

00:40.807 --> 00:41.808
...goodbye.

00:43.376 --> 00:45.512
[instrumental music]

00:45.546 --> 00:47.848
I should never have
let him go in the first place.

00:47.881 --> 00:49.683
I’m going to Mypos.

00:49.716 --> 00:51.484
[theme song]

01:00.594 --> 01:04.197
♪ Sometimes the world
looks perfect ♪

01:04.230 --> 01:06.600
♪ Nothing to rearrange ♪

01:06.633 --> 01:09.603
♪ Sometimes you just
get a feeling ♪

01:09.636 --> 01:12.272
♪ Like you need
some kind of change ♪

01:13.907 --> 01:17.744
♪ No matter what
the odds are this time ♪

01:17.778 --> 01:19.846
♪ Nothing’s going
to stand in my way ♪

01:19.880 --> 01:21.548
♪ This flame in my heart ♪

01:21.582 --> 01:23.383
♪ Like a long lost friend ♪

01:23.416 --> 01:27.287
♪ Gives every dark street
a light at the end ♪

01:28.488 --> 01:31.625
♪ Standing tall ♪

01:31.658 --> 01:35.228
♪ On the wings of my dream ♪

01:35.261 --> 01:38.298
♪ Rise and fall ♪

01:38.331 --> 01:41.802
♪ On the wings of my dream ♪

01:41.835 --> 01:43.469
♪ The rain and thunder ♪

01:43.504 --> 01:45.271
♪ The wind and haze ♪

01:45.305 --> 01:48.542
♪ I’m bound for better days ♪

01:48.575 --> 01:52.145
♪ It’s my life and my dream ♪

01:52.178 --> 01:54.748
♪ Nothing’s going
to stop me now ♪

02:05.458 --> 02:06.860
[instrumental music]

02:35.355 --> 02:37.891
[music continues]

02:51.404 --> 02:52.939
[sheep bleating]

03:06.486 --> 03:08.221
[indistinct chatter]

03:10.023 --> 03:11.758
[music continues]

03:22.536 --> 03:24.671
Hot doggies!
Get them while they’re hot.

03:24.705 --> 03:26.239
Hot doggies!

03:28.041 --> 03:29.710
‐Hello, Balki.
‐Hi.

03:29.743 --> 03:30.777
Hot...

03:34.515 --> 03:37.584
Cousin Larry. Cousin Larry...

03:37.618 --> 03:39.953
What are you doing here?
I can’t believe it’s you.

03:39.986 --> 03:42.322
I... I‐I must be dreaming.

03:42.355 --> 03:44.758
Ow! Ow! Ow! Ow!

03:44.791 --> 03:46.893
You’re not dreaming.
Stop pinching me!

03:46.927 --> 03:47.928
[screams]

03:48.862 --> 03:50.296
It is you!

03:50.330 --> 03:51.965
Oh, cousin, cousin!

03:51.998 --> 03:52.933
Cousin, I... I...

03:52.966 --> 03:55.736
I mean, it’s, it’s
unbelievable. I...

03:55.769 --> 03:57.971
What are you doing here?

03:58.004 --> 04:00.674
Balki, I came
to try one more time

04:00.707 --> 04:02.676
to talk mama into letting you
come back to America.

04:02.709 --> 04:04.678
Oh, cousin

04:04.711 --> 04:06.647
you’re barking up
a dead horse.

04:08.448 --> 04:09.883
Balki,
just let me talk to her.

04:09.916 --> 04:11.685
Well, cousin,
that’s a big no can do.

04:11.718 --> 04:13.386
She’s on the other side
of the island.

04:13.419 --> 04:14.487
Well, let’s go get her.

04:14.521 --> 04:16.389
Well, cousin, we can’t.

04:16.422 --> 04:17.524
Her woman’s group is having

04:17.558 --> 04:20.493
a consciousness raising seminar
and chili cook‐off.

04:22.896 --> 04:24.598
These things can be
really intense.

04:24.631 --> 04:25.932
She’ll be back in a week

04:25.966 --> 04:28.769
more in touch with herself
and reeking of onions.

04:31.437 --> 04:32.873
No problem, I’ll wait.

04:32.906 --> 04:34.708
I took two weeks vacation.

04:34.741 --> 04:36.076
Cousin.

04:36.109 --> 04:38.478
Well, cousin, cousin,
eh, pull up a stool

04:38.512 --> 04:40.714
pull up a stool
and take a load off.

04:46.653 --> 04:48.589
[bell ringing]

05:01.467 --> 05:03.103
What’s goin’ on?

05:03.136 --> 05:04.605
Nap time.

05:08.642 --> 05:10.010
What, for the whole island?

05:10.043 --> 05:11.444
Well, yeah, except for me.

05:11.477 --> 05:13.714
I’m so excited I‐I‐I haven’t

05:13.747 --> 05:15.582
been able to sleep
since you got here.

05:17.417 --> 05:20.554
So, Balki, how are things
goin’ for ya here?

05:20.587 --> 05:22.388
Great! Really great!

05:22.422 --> 05:23.524
Yeah, um...

05:23.557 --> 05:24.658
Uh, they, they had

05:24.691 --> 05:26.627
a big welcome home parade for me

05:26.660 --> 05:29.663
and I’ve been invited
to appear on a local talk show

05:29.696 --> 05:31.431
"Livestock of the Rich
and Famous."

05:32.899 --> 05:33.934
I would’ve thought
you would have been

05:33.967 --> 05:36.369
a little homesick...

05:36.402 --> 05:38.371
...you know, because
of all you left behind.

05:38.404 --> 05:40.106
Uh, your job

05:40.140 --> 05:41.675
your friends

05:41.708 --> 05:43.844
Mary Anne

05:43.877 --> 05:46.446
the coin‐operated horse
outside the Shop ’n Save.

05:49.816 --> 05:51.752
I do miss Blue Thunder.

05:54.154 --> 05:56.489
Cousin, you can read me
like a book on tape.

05:57.858 --> 06:01.027
I am homesick. I...

06:01.061 --> 06:03.597
I... Things are not
the same for me here.

06:03.630 --> 06:06.533
You know, there’s
no urban sprawl

06:06.567 --> 06:08.635
no lines at the movies

06:08.669 --> 06:11.905
no, no unsightly graffiti.

06:14.074 --> 06:15.509
I miss America.

06:16.476 --> 06:18.679
Well, we miss you too.

06:18.712 --> 06:20.881
And so that’s why,
no matter what it takes

06:20.914 --> 06:22.883
I’m gonna take you back.

06:22.916 --> 06:25.418
But, cousin, you know, I don’t
think you’re going to be able

06:25.451 --> 06:27.854
to convince mama
into letting me go.

06:27.888 --> 06:30.123
Once she gets her mind
set on something

06:30.156 --> 06:32.926
you know, she’s,
she’s very pig‐headed.

06:32.959 --> 06:34.895
Well, you let me
worry about mama.

06:35.629 --> 06:37.163
Well, okay, cousin.

06:37.197 --> 06:38.732
Listen, until she comes back

06:38.765 --> 06:40.433
you’ll be staying with me
at mama’s place.

06:40.466 --> 06:42.803
Um... I think
you’re gonna like it.

06:42.836 --> 06:45.639
It’s got central air
and detached chicken coop.

06:49.643 --> 06:51.578
[instrumental music]

07:01.487 --> 07:03.557
[whistling]

07:16.202 --> 07:17.203
[squawk]

07:21.041 --> 07:23.577
Marge, Cousin Larry
might want an omelet too.

07:26.079 --> 07:28.148
[Marge squawking]

07:28.181 --> 07:29.783
[whistling]

07:31.017 --> 07:32.953
[chickens squawking]

07:40.727 --> 07:41.962
Cousin, where have you been?

07:41.995 --> 07:44.030
I got up before dawn
this morning

07:44.064 --> 07:45.832
sat on the hill
overlooking the village.

07:45.866 --> 07:47.568
You know what I saw?

07:47.601 --> 07:48.902
The village?

07:50.203 --> 07:51.805
Well, yeah, that.

07:51.838 --> 07:53.607
But I, I also saw something

07:53.640 --> 07:55.108
truly remarkable.

07:55.141 --> 07:57.611
I saw Mypiots
on their way to work.

07:57.644 --> 07:59.012
They were happy

07:59.045 --> 08:01.782
smiling, saying
"Hello" to each other.

08:01.815 --> 08:04.618
Well, th‐they seemed
to actually enjoy...

08:05.952 --> 08:07.187
...just being alive.

08:08.221 --> 08:10.557
Mmm.

08:10.591 --> 08:12.826
It was a totally
stress‐free environment

08:12.859 --> 08:14.728
there was no rat race.

08:14.761 --> 08:17.698
Well, of course not.
Don’t be ridiculous.

08:17.731 --> 08:19.566
The rat races
are only on Sunday.

08:19.600 --> 08:21.201
We’ve got the, uh

08:21.234 --> 08:24.538
schedule stuck
to the egg dispenser.

08:24.571 --> 08:25.972
Balki, here, look at this.

08:26.006 --> 08:27.040
I picked it myself.

08:27.073 --> 08:28.942
Well, isn’t that something?

08:28.975 --> 08:30.711
You can’t do that in Chicago.

08:30.744 --> 08:33.547
[chuckles]
Life here is good.

08:33.580 --> 08:34.581
[crunching]

08:42.923 --> 08:44.290
What’s wrong
with this apple?

08:44.324 --> 08:46.927
It’s a sour turnip,
only horses eat those.

08:50.864 --> 08:53.900
And a perfectly wonderful
sour turnip it is.

08:53.934 --> 08:55.702
Toss it in here,
we’ll make an omelet.

08:57.804 --> 08:59.272
You know, Balki...

09:01.107 --> 09:03.677
...I’m startin’ to feel
at home here.

09:03.710 --> 09:07.013
Yeah, and, and I think
the villagers like me too.

09:07.047 --> 09:09.315
All morning they’ve been
calling out my name

09:09.349 --> 09:10.651
wherever I go.

09:11.852 --> 09:14.621
"Larry, Larry! Larry, Larry!"

09:15.922 --> 09:17.223
Cousin, I hate
to burst your bubble

09:17.257 --> 09:20.594
but "Larri larri"
is a Myposian phrase.

09:20.627 --> 09:23.163
It means "Sheep crossing,
watch where you step."

09:29.402 --> 09:31.137
Well, that’s right
neighborly of them.

09:33.640 --> 09:35.776
You know, Balki

09:35.809 --> 09:37.844
watching these happy

09:37.878 --> 09:39.880
stress‐free

09:39.913 --> 09:41.882
smiling villagers

09:41.915 --> 09:43.817
well, it made me
realize that...

09:46.052 --> 09:48.088
...well, I wanna be one of ’em.

09:50.123 --> 09:53.393
You know, Balki,
I’ve made a decision.

09:53.426 --> 09:56.362
I am going to stay on Mypos.

09:56.396 --> 09:59.700
Well, cousin, you’re welcome
to stay as long as you like.

09:59.733 --> 10:01.668
By the way, you’re drinking
from the goat’s water bowl.

10:07.674 --> 10:08.675
[indistinct]

10:08.709 --> 10:10.977
No, no, Balki,
you‐you you don’t understand.

10:11.011 --> 10:12.746
See, see.

10:12.779 --> 10:15.215
I belong on Mypos.

10:15.248 --> 10:18.184
I want to live here forever.

10:18.218 --> 10:20.787
I’m gonna call Mr. Wainwright,
quit my job

10:20.821 --> 10:21.755
tell him what I really
think of him.

10:21.788 --> 10:23.389
Now, cousin,
that’s going a little far.

10:23.423 --> 10:24.958
Then I’m gonna call Jennifer,
tell her to sell

10:24.991 --> 10:26.359
everything we own
and get over here.

10:26.392 --> 10:28.128
Speed bump, slow down.

10:28.161 --> 10:29.796
I’m gonna give away
my Maalox

10:29.830 --> 10:31.264
have all my sport coats
made into vests.

10:31.297 --> 10:34.267
Now, cousin, that is just...

10:34.300 --> 10:36.637
Actually the vest idea,
there‐there’s something to that.

10:38.772 --> 10:39.973
But you know, cousin, this is

10:40.006 --> 10:42.175
the dirt is always
browner syndrome.

10:42.208 --> 10:43.977
I went through
the same thing myself.

10:44.010 --> 10:46.713
Remember when we went
to Six Flags for the first time

10:46.747 --> 10:49.082
and I wanted to live
on the log ride?

10:51.284 --> 10:53.219
I came back in a week.

10:55.856 --> 10:59.059
No, no, Balki,
this is the real thing.

10:59.092 --> 11:01.227
Now, cousin, come on,
you’re not serious.

11:01.261 --> 11:03.964
Look, I’ll, I’ll show you
how serious I am.

11:03.997 --> 11:06.366
See this?
My return ticket to Chicago...

11:09.503 --> 11:11.437
Cousin,
you are going to be sorry

11:11.471 --> 11:13.106
you did that in about a week.

11:13.139 --> 11:14.908
However, for the present

11:14.941 --> 11:17.110
I think I can stick this
back together for you.

11:18.178 --> 11:20.881
Balki, do what you want

11:20.914 --> 11:22.448
but I am here to stay.

11:29.122 --> 11:30.356
[instrumental music]

11:34.327 --> 11:36.062
[chickens squawking]

11:41.768 --> 11:42.803
Did you get it?

11:42.836 --> 11:44.170
Yeah, Niko says

11:44.204 --> 11:45.305
this would take
the stains right out.

11:45.338 --> 11:46.439
Oh.

11:46.472 --> 11:47.774
[sighs]

11:51.411 --> 11:53.747
He also said you’re fired.

11:53.780 --> 11:54.981
Fired?

11:55.015 --> 11:57.383
Niko says I was fired? Why?

11:57.417 --> 11:59.986
I‐I was one of the best
grape crushers he had.

12:01.354 --> 12:03.256
He said you drank
too much of the wine.

12:05.058 --> 12:06.459
Cousin, is that true?

12:06.492 --> 12:09.029
No, I didn’t drink
any of the wine.

12:09.062 --> 12:11.431
I fell in the vat.
I was drowning!

12:13.499 --> 12:16.436
Well, that doesn’t get the hair
out of the burgundy, does it?

12:18.471 --> 12:22.308
Oh, this is great.

12:22.342 --> 12:26.179
Niko says I’m not good enough
to step on grapes.

12:26.212 --> 12:29.015
I rub my hands raw trying
to be a butter churner

12:29.049 --> 12:31.151
but Dario says my butter
isn’t spreadable.

12:34.054 --> 12:36.289
I get thrown out of my,
my sheepherding class

12:36.322 --> 12:38.491
because a wolf
ate my training flock.

12:42.495 --> 12:44.397
Who’d have thought
there’d actually be

12:44.430 --> 12:46.366
a wolf in sheep’s clothing?

12:49.903 --> 12:52.205
Cousin, maybe

12:52.238 --> 12:53.439
nine blisters

12:53.473 --> 12:56.176
two purple feet,
and fourteen dead sheep

12:56.209 --> 12:58.845
are a sign that you
really belong in Chicago.

13:00.146 --> 13:01.447
Well...

13:01.481 --> 13:03.850
...Balki, maybe
you’re right.

13:05.018 --> 13:07.187
I mean, who am I kidding?

13:16.329 --> 13:17.898
I’m going back to Chicago.

13:17.931 --> 13:20.433
You, you belong in Chicago.

13:20.466 --> 13:22.202
Well, you know something?

13:22.235 --> 13:23.469
So do you!

13:23.504 --> 13:25.906
I would love
to go back to Chicago

13:25.939 --> 13:28.408
but this is a conversation
you have to have with mama.

13:28.441 --> 13:30.844
When you say to me, you know

13:30.877 --> 13:33.346
it just really bums me out.

13:35.348 --> 13:36.583
Well, Balki...

13:38.351 --> 13:40.220
...there’s got
to be something...

13:42.155 --> 13:44.525
...that we could say
to change her mind.

13:44.558 --> 13:46.627
Cousin, you don’t know mama.

13:46.660 --> 13:48.962
When she gets an idea
in her head

13:48.995 --> 13:50.931
trying to get that idea
out of her head

13:50.964 --> 13:53.366
is like trying to teach
an old frog new tricks.

13:55.301 --> 13:58.104
Now, mama has decided
that she wants me here

13:58.138 --> 13:59.573
and that is that.

13:59.606 --> 14:02.876
I‐I don’t know, cousin,
how I can explain this to you.

14:04.010 --> 14:05.011
[exhales]

14:06.146 --> 14:07.447
Have a seat.

14:11.518 --> 14:14.087
Balki, I came 5000 miles

14:14.120 --> 14:16.389
to try to talk mama into letting
you come back to America.

14:16.422 --> 14:18.258
‐And that’s what I’m gonna do.
‐Well..

14:18.291 --> 14:20.861
♪ She works hard
for the money ♪

14:22.395 --> 14:25.966
♪ So hard for the money ♪

14:25.999 --> 14:28.468
Looks like you’re gonna
get your chance.

14:28.502 --> 14:31.437
♪ ...so you better
treat her right ♪

14:33.373 --> 14:35.509
[humming]

14:36.376 --> 14:38.078
[chickens clucking]

14:40.714 --> 14:41.948
Balki.

14:41.982 --> 14:43.917
‐Balki, babiki!
‐Mama! Oh...

14:45.586 --> 14:46.587
(Balki)
’Oh.’

14:48.421 --> 14:49.923
That’s very nice.

14:49.956 --> 14:52.092
Very nice.

14:52.125 --> 14:54.695
‐Uh, welcome home, mama.
‐Thank you.

14:54.728 --> 14:56.963
‐Mama, guess what?
‐What?

14:56.997 --> 14:59.099
Cousin Larry
has come to visit.

14:59.132 --> 15:00.300
Huh, yeah, right.

15:03.036 --> 15:04.037
Hello, mama.

15:10.143 --> 15:13.179
Mama, we have to talk.

15:13.213 --> 15:18.985
Balki, go ludiki
bang bong poki noki waka yahoo.

15:20.554 --> 15:22.523
Mama, mama, uh

15:22.556 --> 15:24.057
I want to stayiki.

15:24.090 --> 15:28.428
Go ludiki bang bong
poki noki waka yahoo.

15:28.461 --> 15:30.096
Why no stayiki?

15:30.130 --> 15:32.599
[screaming]
Because I’m the mama,
and I said so!

15:37.203 --> 15:40.006
Cousin, if she gets you
in a headlock

15:40.040 --> 15:41.708
just yell,
I’ll be right outside.

15:46.446 --> 15:47.748
Cousin Larry.

15:47.781 --> 15:49.082
Hello, mama.

15:49.115 --> 15:51.685
Hello, hello, yes, yes.

15:53.319 --> 15:55.255
Yes, I, uh...

15:55.288 --> 15:57.357
‐We eat, we eat.
‐Oh, no, I‐I don’t...

15:57.390 --> 15:59.159
‐Oh, yes. Yup.
‐No...

15:59.192 --> 16:01.628
Mama, no, I...

16:01.662 --> 16:04.497
No, mama, I really don’t..

16:04.531 --> 16:05.766
No, I’m not,
I’m not hungry. I...

16:05.799 --> 16:08.602
No, no, Mama...

16:08.635 --> 16:10.470
Nothing. Mama, we...

16:10.504 --> 16:12.072
We have to talk.

16:12.105 --> 16:14.007
‐Cousin Larry, sit down.
‐Oh!

16:14.741 --> 16:16.242
And take a load off.

16:18.579 --> 16:21.481
‐Oh, no, no, mama...
‐Very nice. Very nice.

16:21.515 --> 16:23.416
Mmm, this is a new dish...

16:23.449 --> 16:24.585
[mumbling]

16:24.618 --> 16:26.787
...and I want your take on it.

16:26.820 --> 16:28.154
[coughs]

16:28.188 --> 16:30.524
Oh! Oh, no!
No, no, Cousin Larry!

16:30.557 --> 16:32.225
[coughing]

16:33.727 --> 16:36.663
[speaking in Myposian]

16:46.807 --> 16:48.474
‐Better?
‐Mm, oh, yeah.

16:48.509 --> 16:49.676
Yak juice.

16:49.710 --> 16:50.744
[coughs]

16:54.615 --> 16:57.283
Cousin Larry, Cousin Larry...

16:57.317 --> 16:58.484
‐Yes, yes, yes.
‐Oh, no, mama. No, no.

16:58.519 --> 16:59.753
‐That’s enough. That’s enough.
‐Just a little bit.

16:59.786 --> 17:01.321
Mama, no, mama.

17:01.354 --> 17:03.489
Mama, we’ll, we’ll eat later.

17:03.524 --> 17:06.425
‐Yes. Okay.
‐Al‐alright? Mama.

17:06.459 --> 17:08.194
‐Yes.
‐Mama?

17:08.228 --> 17:09.429
Yes.

17:09.462 --> 17:11.364
We have to talk.

17:11.396 --> 17:12.833
Yi‐yi‐yi‐yi‐yiy!

17:12.866 --> 17:15.401
Ooh! Ooh! Ooh! Ooh!

17:16.435 --> 17:17.604
Sorry!

17:17.637 --> 17:19.472
Oh! Oh!

17:19.506 --> 17:22.275
[indistinct chatter]

17:22.308 --> 17:24.310
Alright. No, here take this.
Take this.

17:25.377 --> 17:26.547
Careful. Alright, alright.

